/** Keyword and library information
 * -------------------------------
 * deal.II step: fluid-structure interaction
 * Keywords: fluid-structure interaction, biharmonic operator, 
 *           finite elements, benchmark computation, 
 *	     monolithic framework 
 *
 * Source code is based on the deal.II.7.0.0 version
 *
* Abstract
* -------- 
* We describe a setting of a non-linear
* fluid-structure interaction problem and the corresponding 
* solution process in the finite element software package deal.II.
* The fluid equations 
* are transformed via the ALE mapping 
* (Arbitrary Lagrangian Eulerian framework)
* to a reference configuration and these are coupled with the structure
* equations
* by a monolithic solution algorithm. To construct the ALE mapping,
* we use a biharmonic equation. 
* Finite differences are used for temporal discretization. The derivation
* is realized in a general manner that serves for different 
* time stepping schemes.
* Spatial discretization is based on a Galerkin finite element scheme. 
* The non-linear system is solved by a Newton method. 
* Here, the Jacobian matrix is constructed by exact 
* computation of the directional derivatives. 
* The implementation in the software library package deal.II 
* serves for the computation of different  
* fluid-structure configurations. Specifically, our 
* geometry data are taken from the fluid-structure benchmark 
* configuration that was proposed
* in 2006 in the "DFG project Fluid-Structure Interaction I: 
* Modelling, Simulation, Optimisation". 
* Our results show that this implementation in deal.II 
* is able to produce comparable findings.   
*
* Short description of the equations to be solved
* -----------------------------------------------
* 1) Solution of the incompressible Navier-Stokes
*    equations (see Equation (1) in the accompanying article)
*    in a laminar regime.
* 2) Solution of nonlinear hyperbolic (in time) structural equations
*    (see Equation (2)) 
*    in which the constitutive stress tensor is governed by the
*    Saint-Venant Kirchhoff law (Equation (4)).
* 3) The coupled problem is formulated in a monolithic
*    setting in which the fluid equations are re-written
*    with the help of the arbitrary Lagrangian-Eulerian (ALE) framework.
*    The coupling is realized by solving the biharmonic Equation (5).
*    The variational setting is provided in Problem 2.1.
* 4) Solution process:
*    To solve the nonlinear coupled problem, a semi-linear
*    form (Equation (8)) is introduced, which can be 
*    used for temporal and spatial discretization, and 
*    finally, as basis for Newton's method (i.e., the 
*    nonlinear solution process; Equation (9)).
*    A short (formal) description how to 
*    compute the directional derivatives is presented
*    in Section 3.1; however this is only an example
*    in two dimensions. The extension of the source code 
*    is straight forward and was used in T. Wick, PhD Thesis
*    University of Heidelberg, 2011.
* 5) Final remark (computation of fluid flows)
*    The solution of fluid flows (without structural coupling)
*    is straight forward by only changing the material ids
*    marked with "1" (for the structure) to "0" (for the fluid) 
*    in the grid file *.inp. With this change, the user
*    might verify the fluid flow benchmark tests 
*    (Lit. M. Schaefer, S. Turek, 1996) 
*/

